WEBVTT

00:06.000 --> 00:12.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

02:57.800 --> 03:00.924
(FOLK ROCK MUSIC PLAYING)

03:13.880 --> 03:15.411
ADELE: Good morning.

03:39.720 --> 03:41.160
(SIGHS)

03:52.320 --> 03:53.931
(ENGINE STARTING)

04:08.240 --> 04:11.279
<i>ADULT HENRY: It was just the two
of us after my father left.</i>

04:11.280 --> 04:13.039
<i>He said I should count
the new baby he had</i>

04:13.040 --> 04:16.238
<i>with his new wife, Marjorie,
as part of my family, too.</i>

04:16.240 --> 04:18.807
<i>Plus Richard, Marjorie's son.</i>

04:19.760 --> 04:22.359
<i>For the most part, my mother
never mentioned my father,</i>

04:22.360 --> 04:25.599
<i>or the woman he was married to now.</i>

04:25.600 --> 04:27.801
<i>GERALD: You could always come
live with Marjorie and me.</i>

04:28.120 --> 04:31.759
I mean, if that was something you
wanted, we can have her evaluated.

04:31.760 --> 04:34.279
No. Mom is great.

04:34.280 --> 04:37.039
She's learning to play the cello.

04:37.040 --> 04:40.039
I just asked because
I get the feeling her...

04:40.040 --> 04:42.447
(SIGHS) That she's getting worse.

04:42.680 --> 04:46.279
<i>ADULT HENRY: I don't think losing
my father broke my mother's heart</i>

04:46.280 --> 04:48.847
<i>but rather, losing love itself.</i>

04:50.280 --> 04:52.239
<i>Even at that age, I understood this</i>

04:52.240 --> 04:54.879
<i>and wanted to make up for
some of the neglect.</i>

04:54.880 --> 04:56.491
<i>ADELE: Oh, what did you do?</i>

04:59.400 --> 05:01.841
- You made all this for me?
- Mmm-hmm.

05:03.040 --> 05:04.279
ADELE: "Husband for a Day."

05:04.280 --> 05:06.448
<i>ADULT HENRY:
I made her a coupon book.</i>

05:06.800 --> 05:09.159
- I cleaned.
- "One week of clean dishes."

05:09.160 --> 05:11.362
<i>Did little chores around the house.</i>

05:11.480 --> 05:13.039
"Handyman."

05:13.040 --> 05:15.242
<i>There was a coupon
for a shoulder rub.</i>

05:15.400 --> 05:17.284
<i>A bubble bath.</i>

05:17.800 --> 05:19.843
<i>I even took her on a date.</i>

05:21.800 --> 05:25.159
A man should know how to dance.

05:25.160 --> 05:29.126
When a man can dance,
the world is his oyster.

05:29.480 --> 05:33.079
<i>Some men just set their hand on
your shoulder or against your back</i>

05:33.080 --> 05:36.887
<i>but there has to be
strong pressure there.</i>

05:37.840 --> 05:40.079
<i>ADULT HENRY: At the time,
I was too young to understand</i>

05:40.080 --> 05:44.359
<i>the part of being husband for a day,
I was not equipped to carry out.</i>

05:44.360 --> 05:48.406
<i>But I sensed my own
terrible inadequacy.</i>

05:50.120 --> 05:54.564
<i>I could feel her loneliness and
longing before I had a name for it.</i>

06:20.560 --> 06:23.199
BANK TELLER:
Hey, Henry. How's your mother?

06:23.200 --> 06:24.401
Fine.

06:24.640 --> 06:27.525
I hope to see her in
here one of these days.

06:50.840 --> 06:53.691
<i>ADULT HENRY: I understood
who my real family was.</i>

06:53.720 --> 06:55.206
(EXHALES)

06:55.920 --> 06:57.360
<i>Her.</i>

06:57.880 --> 06:59.411
(ENGINE STOPS)

07:02.920 --> 07:03.999
<i>Even if that meant</i>

07:04.000 --> 07:08.125
<i>only leaving the house once a month
to pick up supplies at Pricemart.</i>

07:20.600 --> 07:22.404
I think it's this way.

07:33.520 --> 07:35.484
Is it all right if I go
check out the comics?

07:37.560 --> 07:39.046
Um...

07:39.440 --> 07:42.484
Okay. Just don't wander.

07:43.120 --> 07:44.685
I'll be right over there.

08:23.080 --> 08:25.282
I wonder if you could
give me a hand here.

08:27.600 --> 08:29.159
You're bleeding.

08:29.160 --> 08:32.159
Yeah, well, I fell out a window.

08:32.159 --> 08:33.839
We should get help.

08:33.840 --> 08:36.279
No, I wouldn't want
to upset anyone.

08:36.280 --> 08:38.642
Did you come here with
that woman over there?

08:43.960 --> 08:45.321
My mom.

08:45.680 --> 08:48.804
She looks like the kind of
person that could help me.

08:50.280 --> 08:51.319
I... I don't know.

08:51.320 --> 08:55.002
What I want to ask is,
you think she'd give me a ride?

08:57.160 --> 08:58.521
Hmm?

09:28.400 --> 09:30.762
This is my mother, Adele.

09:31.400 --> 09:34.604
Mom, this is Frank.
He needs our help.

09:34.920 --> 09:36.759
You got a good boy here, Adele.

09:36.760 --> 09:39.042
He was kind enough
to offer me a ride.

09:40.160 --> 09:41.521
Oh.

09:42.440 --> 09:43.880
Um...

09:44.760 --> 09:47.645
Well, he may have, but...

09:47.920 --> 09:51.806
We have a big afternoon.
I don't think we can help you.

09:52.600 --> 09:54.290
Well, that's a shame.

09:57.280 --> 09:59.130
I thought we could have a catch.

10:00.120 --> 10:01.970
- I suck at baseball.
- Hey.

10:02.360 --> 10:03.721
Maybe you used to.

10:03.920 --> 10:06.122
Don't you throw around
a ball with your dad?

10:06.200 --> 10:07.599
I only see him on Sundays.

10:07.600 --> 10:09.039
- Oh.
- ADELE: No. I'm sorry.

10:09.040 --> 10:10.159
I won't be any trouble.

10:10.160 --> 10:12.283
We really (STAMMERS)
can't help you.

10:14.880 --> 10:16.081
FRANK: Frankly,

10:16.800 --> 10:18.650
this needs to happen.

10:25.960 --> 10:27.161
(BEEPING)

10:40.320 --> 10:42.522
Oh, here. Why don't
you get in back?

11:08.920 --> 11:10.246
(SIGHS)

11:11.920 --> 11:13.724
Where do you want to go?

11:15.360 --> 11:17.050
Your house.

11:21.840 --> 11:24.725
Just for a few moments,
to rest my legs.

11:49.680 --> 11:52.042
(SIREN WAILING)

12:54.040 --> 12:55.480
(DOOR CLOSES)

13:06.480 --> 13:08.999
You'll have to excuse the mess.

13:09.000 --> 13:10.690
We've been busy.

13:22.440 --> 13:24.290
Nice place.

13:33.200 --> 13:37.599
ADELE:
How do you, uh, take your coffee?

13:37.600 --> 13:39.165
As is.

13:43.880 --> 13:46.606
- How did you hurt your leg?
- (SIGHS)

13:50.520 --> 13:53.405
I'm going to be straight
with you, here, Henry.

13:54.360 --> 13:56.244
I'm not going to lie.

13:57.480 --> 14:00.759
I hurt my leg jumping out of a
second floor window at a hospital

14:00.760 --> 14:03.566
they'd taken me to to
get my appendix out.

14:04.880 --> 14:06.764
At the prison.
That's how I got out.

14:08.240 --> 14:09.441
When?

14:09.760 --> 14:11.041
This morning.

14:12.240 --> 14:13.930
You escaped?

14:15.080 --> 14:16.930
So, now, the police
are looking for you.

14:19.000 --> 14:21.959
I would have gotten further
except for the damn leg.

14:21.960 --> 14:23.685
(WATER BOILING)

14:35.840 --> 14:37.690
(CUTLERY CLANKS)

14:43.840 --> 14:46.646
I'd be grateful if you let
me stay till nightfall.

14:47.280 --> 14:48.999
I'd try and help out.

14:49.000 --> 14:51.123
I wouldn't ask anything of you.

14:52.120 --> 14:53.810
You just did.

14:53.920 --> 14:57.647
Nothing more than a place to lay low
and rest my leg for a few hours.

14:59.960 --> 15:01.439
How do I...

15:01.440 --> 15:03.642
How do I know you won't hurt us?

15:06.600 --> 15:10.009
I've never intentionally
hurt anyone in my life.

15:11.600 --> 15:16.010
You understand how that
could be hard to believe.

15:23.640 --> 15:25.330
Yeah, I do.

15:36.080 --> 15:38.931
How far are the train
tracks from your backyard?

15:39.400 --> 15:40.601
Running?

15:41.000 --> 15:42.361
Limping.

15:43.400 --> 15:45.284
Twenty minutes, maybe.

15:45.640 --> 15:48.879
People come over. Often. Randomly.

15:48.880 --> 15:50.999
Friends, salesmen,
religious people.

15:51.000 --> 15:54.919
I'll make a run for it tonight and I
can stay out of your way until then.

15:54.920 --> 15:57.839
I mean, they'd notice
if I went quiet.

15:57.840 --> 15:59.719
Even for a little bit.

15:59.720 --> 16:01.119
I just escaped from prison.

16:01.120 --> 16:03.239
The last place
I want to go is back.

16:03.240 --> 16:05.761
I'm stronger than you think.

16:06.160 --> 16:07.964
I don't doubt that.

16:14.760 --> 16:17.566
And I won't let anything
happen to my son.

16:22.840 --> 16:24.883
He's in good hands.

16:34.920 --> 16:36.690
(PANTING)

16:40.360 --> 16:41.799
<i>ANCHORWOMAN ON TV:
Welcome back to Action News.</i>

16:41.800 --> 16:43.199
<i>Commuters may have
experienced delays</i>

16:43.200 --> 16:45.719
<i>on their drive home this afternoon.</i>

16:45.720 --> 16:49.606
<i>Roadblocks on Route 73.
Who are police looking for?</i>

16:49.720 --> 16:52.239
<i>Frank Chambers, an inmate
at Stinchfield Prison,</i>

16:52.240 --> 16:54.239
<i>who escaped earlier this morning.</i>

16:54.240 --> 16:56.719
<i>MALE REPORTER:
Captain! Where is Frank Chambers?</i>

16:56.720 --> 16:59.799
<i>Considering his injuries,
we believe he hasn't gotten far.</i>

16:59.800 --> 17:03.527
<i>Now keep in mind that he is
dangerous and quite possibly armed.</i>

17:03.720 --> 17:05.919
<i>ANCHORWOMAN: Chambers was
recovering from appendicitis</i>

17:05.920 --> 17:07.999
<i>on the second floor
of this hospital</i>

17:08.000 --> 17:10.839
<i>when police say, he just
made a jump for it.</i>

17:10.839 --> 17:14.919
<i>Um, I went to check on him and the next
thing I knew, he was out the window.</i>

17:14.920 --> 17:16.719
<i>Authorities would like
to remind our viewers</i>

17:16.720 --> 17:19.679
<i>that this kind of leap
can spell desperation.</i>

17:19.680 --> 17:23.601
<i>Especially in an inmate
serving 18 years for murder.</i>

17:24.079 --> 17:25.878
<i>ANCHORMAN: Coming up next
on the Channel 7 News,</i>

17:25.880 --> 17:28.446
<i>the hottest day in 11
years in New Hampshire.</i>

17:31.080 --> 17:33.123
Didn't happen that way.

17:34.080 --> 17:36.439
Isn't it against the law
to hide a fugitive?

17:36.440 --> 17:38.642
You got a wise son here, Adele.

17:39.600 --> 17:41.848
It's good to know he's
looking out for you.

17:42.760 --> 17:44.644
It's all going to be fine.

17:45.120 --> 17:47.359
It would only be a problem
if someone found Frank here.

17:47.360 --> 17:49.439
And that doesn't need to happen.

17:49.440 --> 17:52.519
He can just lay low for a few
hours, and then keep moving.

17:52.520 --> 17:54.324
That's true enough.

17:55.120 --> 17:59.086
It's still not acceptable to place you
and your family here in jeopardy.

17:59.640 --> 18:03.242
If someone were to come by, it would
need to look like I kidnapped you.

18:04.800 --> 18:07.002
That's why I'm going
to have to tie you up.

18:07.800 --> 18:09.599
It's about keeping up appearances.

18:09.600 --> 18:12.007
I think you understand what I mean.

18:13.320 --> 18:15.329
- Who are you going to...
- Only you.

18:16.560 --> 18:19.399
Henry here knows he doesn't want
anything to happen to his mother.

18:19.400 --> 18:20.726
Right, Henry?

18:22.200 --> 18:23.606
Hmm?

19:58.880 --> 20:00.411
Open these.

20:27.400 --> 20:29.728
(SIMMERING)

20:42.920 --> 20:44.610
Grab a bowl.

21:53.520 --> 21:55.643
(BLOWING)

22:02.400 --> 22:05.649
<i>ADELE: I don't suppose your father
has told you anything about sex.</i>

22:08.400 --> 22:09.719
Most people put all this focus

22:09.720 --> 22:12.999
on the physical changes
you'll be going through soon.

22:13.000 --> 22:14.559
HENRY: It's okay.

22:14.560 --> 22:17.239
They explained everything
in a health assembly.

22:17.240 --> 22:21.445
Well, there's another aspect that your
health teacher is unlikely to explore.

22:22.600 --> 22:26.279
People act as if making love is all
about secretions and body functions.

22:26.280 --> 22:28.209
Mom. It's okay.

22:29.440 --> 22:33.079
For all the discussions of
body parts and hormones,

22:33.080 --> 22:35.965
they forget to mention
how it feels.

22:38.600 --> 22:40.962
<i>There's another kind of hunger.</i>

22:43.280 --> 22:45.801
<i>The hunger for human touch.</i>

22:48.600 --> 22:50.165
<i>Desire.</i>

22:52.640 --> 22:55.650
<i>People never tell you
about how it feels.</i>

22:58.120 --> 22:59.845
<i>The longing.</i>

23:13.640 --> 23:15.649
What time do the trains
start in the morning?

23:19.160 --> 23:20.691
I don't know.

23:21.720 --> 23:24.764
I'll just have to keep an
ear out for them, I guess.

25:47.920 --> 25:49.360
(SLURPS)

25:58.760 --> 26:01.770
FRANK:
I don't blame you for wondering.

26:03.200 --> 26:07.200
Just know that there's more to this story
than you'll see in that paper there.

26:11.480 --> 26:13.364
How did you escape?

26:15.000 --> 26:20.047
I told the guard at the hospital if he
left, I was going to jump out the window.

26:20.760 --> 26:23.611
He heard that and
went to have a smoke.

26:25.400 --> 26:28.046
Nothing misleads
people like the truth.

26:34.600 --> 26:36.802
You have any brothers or sisters?

26:38.760 --> 26:40.962
(STAMMERS) No. My mom tried, but...

26:42.680 --> 26:45.439
I've got a stepbrother
and a half-sister.

26:45.440 --> 26:48.041
My dad takes me out to
dinner with them on Sundays.

26:49.040 --> 26:52.403
How does a fellow let a woman
like your mother get away?

26:54.920 --> 26:57.009
He got together with his secretary.

26:58.520 --> 26:59.801
Good riddance.

27:02.240 --> 27:03.601
Good morning.

27:07.400 --> 27:09.409
We won't be needing
that any longer.

27:10.080 --> 27:14.205
But if the day comes and you have to
say I tied you up, you won't be lying.

27:17.920 --> 27:20.248
Haven't heard any trains go by.

27:21.560 --> 27:23.091
Holiday weekend.

27:25.720 --> 27:27.126
Breakfast?

27:27.920 --> 27:29.929
You have to try one.

27:33.280 --> 27:34.811
Okay.

27:52.760 --> 27:54.769
(SOFT MUSIC PLAYING)

28:15.640 --> 28:18.525
FRANK: Hey, give me a
three-quarter-inch ratchet wrench.

28:29.520 --> 28:31.479
Ratchet wrench.

28:31.480 --> 28:33.759
<i>ADULT HENRY: That day,
Frank changed the oil in the car</i>

28:33.760 --> 28:36.639
<i>and replaced the fuse
for the blinkers.</i>

28:36.640 --> 28:39.650
<i>Then he replaced the
filter on the furnace.</i>

28:45.160 --> 28:47.999
<i>He checked out the cord of
firewood that just got delivered</i>

28:48.000 --> 28:50.885
<i>and informed my mom that
the guy was shorting her.</i>

28:52.200 --> 28:55.563
<i>Then he washed the
floor and waxed it.</i>

28:57.200 --> 28:58.731
<i>FRANK: Then you rotate the ball.</i>

28:58.880 --> 29:00.411
Grip it loose.

29:01.200 --> 29:03.879
Two fingers up top,
thumb on the bottom.

29:03.880 --> 29:07.402
Just let it rest there.
Barely tight enough to hold.

29:08.360 --> 29:10.879
And when you release,

29:10.880 --> 29:13.719
snap your wrist down, like a whip.

29:13.720 --> 29:15.251
Just crack.

29:15.560 --> 29:19.242
<i>And then you grab those seams
when the ball leaves your fingers.</i>

29:39.520 --> 29:41.449
You bite your lip when you sew.

29:42.440 --> 29:44.079
(EXHALES SOFTLY)

29:44.080 --> 29:46.248
I'm trying not to stick you.

29:56.920 --> 29:58.451
How'd you get that scar?

29:59.120 --> 30:00.399
(ADELE CHUCKLES)

30:00.400 --> 30:04.241
<i>Stars and Stripes Forever</i>
routine for my dance recital.

30:04.440 --> 30:07.450
Halfway through rehearsal,
they got rid of the ramp.

30:07.880 --> 30:10.560
I tapped myself right
off the stage.

30:13.400 --> 30:15.090
(POUNDING ON DOOR)

30:16.960 --> 30:18.969
Come here! Come here!

30:20.240 --> 30:21.919
Answer the door, Hank.

30:21.920 --> 30:23.770
Let them know your mother's out.

30:24.600 --> 30:27.559
And I trust you're not gonna
get nervous and say something.

30:27.560 --> 30:29.000
Now go.

30:32.000 --> 30:33.239
Oh.

30:33.240 --> 30:35.090
Hi, Henry. I was looking
for your mother.

30:36.280 --> 30:38.642
(STAMMERS) I'm sorry,
Mr. Jervis, she's not home.

30:39.640 --> 30:41.330
Oh. Well, that's...

30:41.800 --> 30:43.684
That's not like her.

30:44.600 --> 30:48.319
Has she been following
the news, do you know?

30:48.320 --> 30:50.522
Did she leave you here by yourself?

30:51.480 --> 30:53.919
No, I just mean she
can't come to the door.

30:53.920 --> 30:56.009
- She's taking a bath.
- MR. JERVIS: Oh.

30:58.320 --> 30:59.959
Are those for her?

30:59.960 --> 31:03.479
Yeah. I had so many, I didn't
know what to do with them.

31:03.480 --> 31:05.011
I thought your mother
might like them.

31:05.320 --> 31:06.639
Thank you.

31:06.640 --> 31:08.524
I'm sure she'll appreciate them.

31:09.680 --> 31:13.965
Let her know there's something
I'd like to discuss with her.

31:15.320 --> 31:17.204
Is everything okay?

31:18.720 --> 31:20.843
MR. JERVIS: Well, uh...

31:21.520 --> 31:25.519
Look, Henry, I don't know if you've
heard, but there's a guy loose.

31:25.520 --> 31:27.370
Broke out of Stinchfield.

31:28.000 --> 31:31.639
He's probably long gone
by now, but till they find him,

31:31.640 --> 31:34.844
I wouldn't be opening the
door without an adult.

31:35.960 --> 31:37.839
Thank you for telling me.

31:37.840 --> 31:41.408
Look, I doubt he's
anywhere near here by now.

31:42.200 --> 31:44.368
Just remember, I'm right
across the street.

31:44.680 --> 31:47.850
You have any problems,
just give me a jingle.

31:55.080 --> 31:56.879
(ADELE PANTING)

31:56.880 --> 31:58.525
He had more than he needed.

32:02.000 --> 32:03.611
You did good, Hank.

32:08.360 --> 32:09.891
Um...

32:10.400 --> 32:12.921
Henry, why don't you
go check on Joe?

32:13.720 --> 32:15.081
I'm sure he's fine.

32:15.400 --> 32:17.199
It's a hot day.

32:17.200 --> 32:19.607
Make sure his water
hasn't dried up.

32:20.280 --> 32:21.641
Yeah.

32:28.560 --> 32:30.091
You can't do that again.

32:30.400 --> 32:31.759
What? What did I do?

32:31.760 --> 32:34.122
My son is not your lookout.

32:35.080 --> 32:36.359
He's not your accomplice.
And I don't...

32:36.360 --> 32:38.767
- it was just a neighbor.
- It doesn't matter!

32:45.520 --> 32:47.079
Don't forget what's going on here.

32:47.080 --> 32:49.089
Not for a second.

32:49.560 --> 32:51.410
Now, I see the way he looks at you.

32:52.000 --> 32:53.559
What he wants.

32:53.560 --> 32:55.410
That encouragement,
pat on his shoulder.

32:55.680 --> 32:57.769
And I want it for him.

32:59.000 --> 33:00.725
But not for that.

33:03.520 --> 33:06.564
I can't promise what's going
to show up at the door.

33:08.040 --> 33:09.401
I know.

33:13.080 --> 33:14.611
Okay, then.

33:25.080 --> 33:26.645
(EXHALES)

33:33.760 --> 33:35.485
It's a good peach.

33:37.600 --> 33:40.371
It's too bad they're all so ripe,
you'll never get through them all.

33:41.280 --> 33:44.484
We should throw most of
them away before they rot.

33:46.120 --> 33:48.163
No, I have another idea.

33:50.960 --> 33:52.559
Take a peach.

33:52.560 --> 33:53.799
HENRY: Thank you.

33:53.800 --> 33:56.606
<i>FRANK: Now, the filling is easy.
What I want to talk about is crust.</i>

33:57.080 --> 33:59.399
<i>You've got to keep
your ingredients cool.</i>

33:59.400 --> 34:01.967
<i>Hot day like this is
challenge enough.</i>

34:03.640 --> 34:07.640
The phone rings while you're making
a crust, just let them call you back.

34:18.159 --> 34:19.646
Mix it up.

34:36.440 --> 34:37.801
(SIGHS)

34:48.000 --> 34:51.518
Pie crust is a very
forgiving thing. Forks.

34:51.520 --> 34:54.768
You can make all kinds of mistakes,
but don't forget the salt.

34:55.840 --> 34:58.719
ADELE: All of it?
FRANK: Yeah, before it gets too warm.

34:58.720 --> 35:00.399
Keep everything cool.

35:00.400 --> 35:02.409
Then mix it up.

35:03.560 --> 35:05.444
Take that knife.

35:09.920 --> 35:12.282
It's all about instinct.

35:12.360 --> 35:15.769
Pay too much attention to
recipes, you forget how to feel.

35:17.200 --> 35:18.719
It's like reading a
book on gardening

35:18.720 --> 35:21.491
when all you've got to do is get
dirt underneath your fingernails.

35:26.880 --> 35:28.719
All right. Put it in there.

35:28.720 --> 35:30.251
That's it.

35:30.880 --> 35:32.605
Now, don't over-handle.

35:33.240 --> 35:37.126
You want it right on the verge
of crumbling at any moment.

35:37.520 --> 35:39.051
There you go.

35:51.560 --> 35:53.489
Now grab the outside.

35:54.240 --> 35:56.169
Heel of the hand.

35:58.240 --> 36:00.079
People buy all these fancy gadgets,

36:00.080 --> 36:04.330
but sometimes the best tool is
attached right there to your own body.

36:05.080 --> 36:06.566
Okay.

36:10.920 --> 36:14.919
Scatter a little tapioca,
like salt over an icy road.

36:14.920 --> 36:16.963
Cure for a soggy crust.

36:18.440 --> 36:20.290
The whole thing.

36:24.600 --> 36:26.768
Make a little mountain out of it.

36:28.760 --> 36:30.325
Perfect.

36:42.440 --> 36:44.483
Okay, moment of truth.

36:46.800 --> 36:48.490
Can't go too fast.

36:50.640 --> 36:52.330
You can't hesitate.

36:57.600 --> 36:59.519
<i>ADULT HENRY:
I don't know when my mom's hands</i>

36:59.520 --> 37:01.688
<i>started shaking exactly.</i>

37:02.280 --> 37:05.165
<i>But eventually, it was
beyond her control.</i>

37:06.040 --> 37:08.527
(TREMBLING)

37:11.160 --> 37:13.522
Help me put a roof on this house.

37:21.000 --> 37:22.361
Perfect.

38:05.800 --> 38:07.923
(BEEPING)

39:16.560 --> 39:18.489
(TRAIN WHISTLE BLOWING IN THE DISTANCE)

39:22.120 --> 39:23.606
I should go.

39:25.800 --> 39:27.439
They won't come back
for a few hours.

39:27.440 --> 39:29.449
This is as good a window
as I'm gonna get.

39:33.160 --> 39:35.681
Maybe tomorrow,

39:36.400 --> 39:39.126
once your stitches have
had a little more time.

39:39.760 --> 39:42.639
They're not going to
stop looking, Adele.

39:42.640 --> 39:45.127
HENRY: They have dogs that
can smell your blood.

39:47.800 --> 39:50.128
You should probably let
your stitches heal.

39:52.440 --> 39:54.210
You should stay.

40:04.800 --> 40:07.159
ADELE:
Thank you. I'm really nervous.

40:07.160 --> 40:09.044
You have to...

40:09.160 --> 40:10.839
FRANK: I understand.

40:10.840 --> 40:12.999
We'll just lay here a while.

40:13.000 --> 40:18.525
ADELE: We haven't had anybody in
this house for such a long time.

40:20.320 --> 40:22.204
Let me get my...

40:25.280 --> 40:27.562
(ADELE AND FRANK MOANING)

40:36.840 --> 40:38.201
<i>ADULT HENRY: Rhythm.</i>

40:39.160 --> 40:41.559
<i>This was the word that
burrowed into my brain</i>

40:41.560 --> 40:45.560
<i>as I listened to their late night
conversation quietly dissipate.</i>

40:46.520 --> 40:49.883
<i>I thought about
that word, "rhythm,"</i>

40:50.480 --> 40:53.411
<i>and whether my mom
thought Frank had it.</i>

40:55.520 --> 40:58.769
<i>These were the images
I returned to at night.</i>

41:00.040 --> 41:03.799
<i>Particularly now that the
evening was no longer silent.</i>

41:03.800 --> 41:06.082
(MOANING CONTINUES)

41:43.880 --> 41:48.085
<i>ADULT HENRY: The next day, Frank
fixed the loose floorboard on the stairs.</i>

41:51.120 --> 41:52.279
(SQUEAKING)

41:52.280 --> 41:55.279
<i>He got the squeak out
of the kitchen door,</i>

41:55.280 --> 41:57.960
<i>then cleared the debris
out of the gutters.</i>

42:04.600 --> 42:06.165
Thank you.

42:14.800 --> 42:16.319
I'll tell you this.

42:16.320 --> 42:19.239
You don't want to wait
to learn to fix it.

42:19.240 --> 42:23.331
Especially if you got a lady in the
seat beside you when it happens.

42:26.120 --> 42:29.479
<i>ADULT HENRY:
They did laundry. He ironed.</i>

42:29.480 --> 42:32.251
<i>And in return, my mom
taught him to rumba.</i>

42:32.320 --> 42:35.683
Two... three... four.

42:35.800 --> 42:37.559
Shift your weight this way.

42:37.560 --> 42:40.843
Two... three... four.

42:41.320 --> 42:42.559
<i>ADULT HENRY:
For lunch, Frank thought</i>

42:42.560 --> 42:44.639
<i>it only right that we
fire up the barbecue.</i>

42:44.640 --> 42:47.081
<i>So, he sent me to
pick up groceries.</i>

43:11.160 --> 43:12.850
(BELL JINGLING)

43:45.480 --> 43:48.411
You know, drinking from
aluminum gives you Alzheimer's.

43:49.320 --> 43:51.039
Is that true?

43:51.040 --> 43:52.199
Uh-huh.

43:52.200 --> 43:53.399
It's the perfect crime

43:53.400 --> 43:55.409
'cause you can't
remember how you got it.

43:57.400 --> 43:59.648
Is there anything
to do in this town?

44:01.400 --> 44:03.250
There's bowling?

44:06.880 --> 44:08.445
Bowling.

44:11.640 --> 44:13.719
GROCER: If you ask me, I think
he's holing up in someone's house

44:13.720 --> 44:15.359
waiting for things to cool down.

44:15.360 --> 44:18.079
SHOPPER: I just can't get
his face out of my head.

44:18.080 --> 44:21.124
The worst part is knowing that a
man like that has nothing to lose.

44:21.360 --> 44:23.879
Life to a person like that
is worth about 10 cents.

44:23.880 --> 44:25.759
They'll get him eventually.
They always do.

44:25.760 --> 44:28.804
- Henry. How's your mother?
- She's doing great.

44:29.880 --> 44:31.399
Where's all the canned goods?

44:31.400 --> 44:33.559
You usually buy like you're
planning for a tornado.

44:33.560 --> 44:35.888
Yeah. Special recipe.

44:37.600 --> 44:39.079
Henry. This is a man's razor.

44:39.080 --> 44:41.439
Your mom wants one of the
pink ones on aisle 7.

44:41.440 --> 44:43.130
It's not for my mom.

44:44.400 --> 44:45.931
It's for me.

44:46.920 --> 44:48.281
You practicing?

44:50.720 --> 44:53.605
All right. Just do me a favor
and keep the cap on, okay?

45:04.280 --> 45:06.084
Keep an eye out, all right?

45:08.360 --> 45:10.164
(CAR DOOR OPENS)

45:13.960 --> 45:15.161
(CAR DOOR CLOSES)

45:19.240 --> 45:20.726
Mom?

45:27.360 --> 45:29.324
ADELE: You were just a boy.

45:29.800 --> 45:31.843
FRANK: I was 21.

45:33.800 --> 45:36.119
ADELE: You didn't know
what you were doing.

45:36.120 --> 45:37.479
FRANK: Doesn't make it right.

45:37.480 --> 45:40.490
ADELE:
Why didn't you say something?

46:05.520 --> 46:07.210
EVELYN: Adele?

46:11.840 --> 46:13.679
Hey, Henry, where's your mom?

46:13.680 --> 46:15.086
(STAMMERS) I don't know!

46:16.000 --> 46:18.123
Um, let me go... Let me
go get her. Stay here!

46:18.200 --> 46:20.880
EVELYN: I need you to watch Barry!

46:24.160 --> 46:25.719
ADELE: Ev, hi!

46:25.720 --> 46:27.719
She asked me to watch Barry.

46:27.720 --> 46:31.242
EVELYN: Listen. I'm at my wits' end.
I really need some help from you.

46:32.040 --> 46:34.561
I have to go.
My dad's in the hospital.

46:34.840 --> 46:36.359
ADELE: Oh, my God. I'm sorry.

46:36.360 --> 46:38.839
EVELYN:
So I need somebody to watch Barry.

46:38.840 --> 46:40.610
ADELE: Like, right now?
EVELYN: Yeah.

46:41.880 --> 46:44.082
Yeah, I'll be back tonight.

46:45.040 --> 46:46.879
ADELE: You know, I can't. Um...

46:46.880 --> 46:50.359
- Hey, Barry. How's it going?
- Good.

46:50.360 --> 46:51.999
They don't expect my dad
to hold on for long.

46:52.000 --> 46:53.079
Yeah, normally...

46:53.080 --> 46:55.279
I really don't have any
other options, Adele.

46:55.280 --> 46:57.519
I know. (STAMMERS)
I really want to help you.

46:57.520 --> 46:59.359
I promise he'll be good.

46:59.360 --> 47:01.439
You're gonna be good, right, Barry?

47:01.440 --> 47:03.599
You remember Henry? And his mom?

47:03.600 --> 47:06.007
And all the good times
you've had here?

47:06.880 --> 47:08.039
Evelyn.

47:08.040 --> 47:10.399
Please. One mother to another.

47:10.400 --> 47:11.879
I would not ask you if
I wasn't desperate.

47:11.880 --> 47:12.919
It's just that...

47:12.920 --> 47:15.600
I don't have any
other options. Please.

47:17.080 --> 47:19.328
- You're not going anywhere.
- (SIGHS)

47:24.400 --> 47:25.647
- Okay.
- Thank you.

47:25.760 --> 47:28.439
Thank you, thank you. I owe you.

47:28.440 --> 47:31.799
I will be back by the end of the night.
It's about two hours' drive.

47:31.800 --> 47:32.879
Ah, okay.

47:32.880 --> 47:34.919
EVELYN: Just put his chair
in front of the TV.

47:34.920 --> 47:36.485
He loves cartoons.

47:36.880 --> 47:38.127
Okay. Um...

47:40.120 --> 47:42.971
Come on. I'll get you inside.

47:43.280 --> 47:44.811
Here we go.

47:45.120 --> 47:46.651
The door.

47:56.280 --> 48:00.079
Hey, Barry, you look mighty
toasty in all those clothes.

48:00.080 --> 48:03.807
I swear, she dresses him
for winter in August.

48:09.320 --> 48:12.319
Well, you got here just in time.

48:12.320 --> 48:14.329
We needed a third baseman.

48:30.840 --> 48:33.884
Now, Barry, my name's Frank.

48:33.920 --> 48:35.319
(MUMBLES)

48:35.320 --> 48:37.363
That's right. Frank.

48:37.840 --> 48:39.371
There you go.

48:42.960 --> 48:44.491
All right. Let's see that swing.

48:44.680 --> 48:46.564
Don't get your hopes up.

48:46.800 --> 48:49.359
Want to run that by me again?

48:49.360 --> 48:51.519
Bat up. Shoulders forward.

48:51.520 --> 48:54.041
Choke up on the bat,
hands together.

48:54.480 --> 48:56.011
Knees bent.

48:56.880 --> 48:58.159
There we go. Good.

48:58.160 --> 49:00.679
When I throw it
to you, see the ball.

49:00.680 --> 49:03.479
- See the ball.
- See the ball.

49:03.480 --> 49:04.920
Keep it fluid.

49:08.320 --> 49:09.726
- There we go.
- BARRY: Whoa!

49:10.320 --> 49:11.851
HENRY: See the ball.

49:15.200 --> 49:20.406
<i>ADULT HENRY: The thing was,
when Frank threw the ball, I hit it.</i>

49:22.720 --> 49:26.242
<i>FRANK: If I had more time to work with
you, we could really get somewhere.</i>

49:27.040 --> 49:29.766
You ready? Your turn?

49:29.800 --> 49:31.525
(PANTING)

49:31.680 --> 49:33.211
- No, no.
- Come on.

49:35.040 --> 49:37.004
- FRANK: Take a deep breath.
- (INHALES DEEPLY)

49:38.880 --> 49:40.279
Relax.

49:40.280 --> 49:43.131
There you go. Bend your knees.

49:43.720 --> 49:45.285
Hands together.

49:47.680 --> 49:48.919
There you go.

49:48.920 --> 49:50.599
- I can't do this.
- Yeah, you can.

49:50.600 --> 49:53.485
You are doing it. Bend your knees.

49:53.560 --> 49:55.808
- Ready?
- (LAUGHS)

49:56.240 --> 49:58.124
Bring on the heat, Hank.

50:00.920 --> 50:03.441
- There you go.
- Whoa!

50:03.600 --> 50:05.768
(CHUCKLING)

50:30.600 --> 50:32.959
<i>ANNOUNCER ON RADIO:
The count is 2 and 2.</i>

50:32.960 --> 50:34.959
<i>The Red Sox are leading, 4 to 0.</i>

50:34.960 --> 50:37.322
<i>Cleveland batting
in the 5th inning.</i>

50:38.120 --> 50:40.846
<i>All four Red Sox runs in the 2nd.</i>

51:21.040 --> 51:23.720
(INAUDIBLE)

51:39.520 --> 51:41.449
(CAR DOOR CLOSES)

51:42.920 --> 51:44.804
You fool.

51:55.920 --> 51:58.122
(INDISTINCT MUSIC ON TV)

52:33.560 --> 52:37.119
<i>Tonight at 11:00, more on
escaped convict Frank Chambers.</i>

52:37.120 --> 52:40.079
<i>Our psychologist weighs
in on what to expect</i>

52:40.080 --> 52:43.159
<i>from a murderer on the run and
where he might be hiding.</i>

52:43.160 --> 52:45.283
<i>That and more at 11:00.</i>

52:51.080 --> 52:52.964
(VEHICLE APPROACHES)

53:01.160 --> 53:03.359
ADELE: (SIGHS) Okay, Barry.

53:03.360 --> 53:05.722
Looks like your mother is here.

53:15.360 --> 53:16.719
- Hi.
- Hi.

53:16.720 --> 53:17.959
How's your dad?

53:17.960 --> 53:21.879
Oh. It's complicated and not all
good, but he's under supervision.

53:21.880 --> 53:23.799
Did you have a good time today?

53:23.800 --> 53:25.331
Yee-yeah!

53:25.440 --> 53:26.639
<i>ANCHORWOMAN ON TV:
This is Lynn Jolicoeur</i>

53:26.640 --> 53:27.879
<i>for News Four New Hampshire.</i>

53:27.880 --> 53:30.599
<i>Tonight's top story is
our continuing coverage</i>

53:30.600 --> 53:33.679
<i>of the escape of Stinchfield
Prison inmate Frank Chambers,</i>

53:33.680 --> 53:35.166
<i>a convicted murderer.</i>

53:35.280 --> 53:37.559
Well, we've had a busy day, so...

53:37.560 --> 53:39.679
EVELYN: Uh, listen, I've been
on the road for two hours.

53:39.680 --> 53:41.530
Could I trouble you
for a glass of water?

53:41.840 --> 53:42.919
Uh, sure.

53:42.920 --> 53:45.521
Henry, would you grab
Evelyn some water?

53:45.880 --> 53:47.719
<i>ANCHORWOMAN:
leaving police with very few clues.</i>

53:47.720 --> 53:49.081
EVELYN: So, was he difficult?

53:50.400 --> 53:54.047
No. No, not at all. No. We had
the best time with Barry.

53:54.160 --> 53:56.199
We went outside and
threw a ball around.

53:56.200 --> 53:58.039
EVELYN:
Oh, God. Did you put on sunscreen?

53:58.040 --> 53:59.479
- ADELE: Yeah. Of course.
- (MUMBLES)

53:59.480 --> 54:01.079
EVELYN:
A lot of people don't do that.

54:01.080 --> 54:03.442
Fwah. Fwah. Fwah!

54:03.600 --> 54:05.239
Yes, I know. We're going.

54:05.240 --> 54:06.879
Fwah, Fwah, Fwah!

54:06.880 --> 54:07.999
(SIGHS) Oh, God.

54:08.000 --> 54:11.839
Okay, okay. We're going home.
I just need a sip of water.

54:11.840 --> 54:12.879
Fwah!

54:12.880 --> 54:15.039
<i>Leaving Labor Day motorists with
more than the usual delays.</i>

54:15.040 --> 54:16.319
Fwrank!

54:16.320 --> 54:18.839
We're gonna watch television
when we get home.

54:18.840 --> 54:20.883
Fwranh! Fwrank!

54:24.760 --> 54:26.041
Stop it!

54:30.760 --> 54:32.644
He needs some rest.

54:39.960 --> 54:41.844
(CAR ENGINE STARTS)

54:58.800 --> 55:01.639
ADELE: You were so young.
Why didn't you appeal?

55:01.640 --> 55:05.526
FRANK: I don't know. I thought
I got what I deserved.

55:05.880 --> 55:07.799
ADELE: But you don't feel that now.

55:07.800 --> 55:09.684
FRANK: No, now it doesn't matter.

55:11.800 --> 55:15.686
You couldn't take a lot.
Might seem suspicious.

55:16.160 --> 55:19.204
ADELE: We just start driving?
Just like that?

55:20.240 --> 55:22.363
FRANK: You couldn't tell
any of your friends.

55:22.640 --> 55:24.444
ADELE: No one to tell, really.

55:27.000 --> 55:30.682
I can't imagine you not being free.

55:31.680 --> 55:36.727
FRANK: I can't call myself free until I can
walk down the street, arm around you.

55:38.000 --> 55:39.531
I'd like that.

55:40.680 --> 55:44.043
FRANK: Take you on road trips
to places we don't know a soul.

55:45.080 --> 55:46.639
ADELE: (CHUCKLES) Like on the run?

55:46.640 --> 55:47.799
FRANK: Mmm-hmm.

55:47.800 --> 55:50.162
That's right. On the run.

55:51.680 --> 55:54.884
My ex-husband would never
let me take Henry away.

55:56.280 --> 55:58.130
FRANK:
You know what that would mean.

55:59.680 --> 56:00.961
ADELE: I know.

56:02.680 --> 56:04.119
FRANK: All right, then.

56:04.120 --> 56:05.959
I noticed a spot under the shower

56:05.960 --> 56:09.519
where the water is finding
its way under the linoleum.

56:09.520 --> 56:13.566
You don't want dry rot.
I'll tackle that tomorrow, okay?

56:15.360 --> 56:17.403
ADELE: Maybe it doesn't matter.

56:36.640 --> 56:38.251
What do you want to do?

56:40.160 --> 56:41.441
<i>HENRY: I don't know.</i>

56:45.400 --> 56:47.125
<i>ELEANOR: I think you know.</i>

56:48.840 --> 56:50.371
Come on.

56:51.080 --> 56:52.441
Just say it.

56:56.200 --> 56:57.731
<i>ELEANOR: What's the matter?</i>

57:04.840 --> 57:06.371
FRANK: Is it cold?

57:07.600 --> 57:09.450
ADELE: You're a tough guy.

57:09.520 --> 57:10.879
I think you could take it.

57:10.880 --> 57:13.759
FRANK:
Is it too cold to grow things?

57:13.760 --> 57:15.803
ADELE: It's mostly farms.

57:17.760 --> 57:19.644
FRANK: It sounds nice.

57:22.280 --> 57:24.164
Morning, sport.

57:25.280 --> 57:26.641
Hey.

57:27.280 --> 57:29.279
How'd you sleep?

57:29.280 --> 57:30.641
Fine.

57:32.040 --> 57:35.799
Um, I was wondering if you
could do me a little favor.

57:35.800 --> 57:37.650
Top secret research.

57:38.200 --> 57:39.639
Research?

57:39.640 --> 57:43.367
Just a trip to the library to pick
up a book on Prince Edward Island.

57:45.960 --> 57:48.083
FRANK:
Your mom says it's beautiful.

57:49.560 --> 57:51.683
<i>ADELE:
Can you pick up the book, Hank?</i>

58:53.200 --> 58:55.641
So, do you go to
school around here?

58:58.720 --> 59:00.279
(STAMMERS)
I'm sorry, I didn't mean to...

59:00.280 --> 59:02.164
ELEANOR:
I just moved here from Chicago.

59:02.440 --> 59:05.086
I'm supposed to try out
living with my dad this year.

59:05.440 --> 59:06.719
Oh.

59:06.720 --> 59:08.081
What happened?

59:09.040 --> 59:11.279
The official reason is
I have an eating disorder

59:11.280 --> 59:14.559
and they think a new school
environment will help.

59:14.560 --> 59:17.359
But really, I think my mom
just wanted to get rid of me

59:17.360 --> 59:19.639
so she can fool around
with her boyfriend.

59:19.640 --> 59:21.559
I understand.

59:21.560 --> 59:25.162
This guy, he just moved
in with my mom and me.

59:25.640 --> 59:27.604
And now he wants you out.

59:27.880 --> 59:30.208
- I don't think so.
- ELEANOR: He will.

59:30.400 --> 59:32.443
So they can have sex.

59:36.080 --> 59:37.639
So, what are you reading?

59:37.640 --> 59:40.399
I'm investigating my legal rights.

59:40.400 --> 59:42.439
You see, I got into this
really great private school

59:42.440 --> 59:44.759
where they only focus on drama.

59:44.760 --> 59:47.611
No one cares about sports or
what kind of clothes you wear.

59:48.000 --> 59:49.839
The teachers stay off your case.

59:49.840 --> 59:51.451
It's really elevated.

59:52.000 --> 59:55.568
But at the last minute, my parents
decided they didn't have the money.

59:55.920 --> 59:57.199
Could they get a loan?

59:57.200 --> 59:59.599
Oh, they have the money.

59:59.600 --> 01:00:02.531
They're just using me as a
pawn in their sick little game.

01:00:05.680 --> 01:00:07.245
What's that?

01:00:08.760 --> 01:00:10.719
It's for my mother.

01:00:10.720 --> 01:00:13.491
She wants to know if Canada
might be a good place to move.

01:00:13.600 --> 01:00:15.245
And how do you feel about that?

01:00:15.680 --> 01:00:18.008
Moving. Leaving your friends.

01:00:18.360 --> 01:00:20.359
I'm asking because
that's what I had to do.

01:00:20.360 --> 01:00:23.404
And frankly,
I consider it child abuse.

01:00:23.800 --> 01:00:26.480
I don't know. Canada seems nice.

01:00:27.040 --> 01:00:28.844
Do you even know if
they're taking you?

01:00:30.120 --> 01:00:31.999
My mom wouldn't leave me behind.

01:00:32.000 --> 01:00:33.959
When people have sex,
it affects their brains.

